                     ) complex. The order of Eint and % reduction in H-Lgaps are the same for analyte@Ag6 complexes i.e. O2@Ag6 > NH3@Ag6 > C2H5OH@Ag6 > H2S@Ag6. Oxygen molecule strongly interacts with silver cluster due to strong Ag⋯O electrostatic interactions. Charge transfer interactions are explored through natural bond orbital (NBO) and charge decomposition (CDA) analyses. The frontier molecular orbital (FMO) analysis reveals a significant reduction in H-Lgap in the complexes of analytes with silver-coronene composites. UV–Visible results show that the absorption maximum is shifted towards a longer wavelength (bathochromic or red shift) in most of the complexes. Non-covalent interaction (NCI) study reveals that, besides strong electrostatic interactions, weak van der Waals dispersion interactions are present in silver-coronene complexes of analytes. The generation of new energy states in occupied and virtual orbitals closer to the Fermi level in the density of state (DOS) spectra affirm the sensitivity of silver-coronene composites towards analytes. The current findings suggest that silver-coronene composites are highly selective for the sensing of oxygen molecule. The outcome of the recent study will help to design the silver-graphene sensors for selective and accurate detection of analytes.

ce:section.ce:para:
“Geometry optimization is performed with several possible orientations ((4–9 configurations)) of each analyte over the substrate (coronene, Ag6, Ag6-coronene and coronene-Ag6) to find the lowest energy structure for each complex. The interaction energies of the most stable configurations are mentioned in the manuscript (Table 1
                        ) whereas the interaction energies of the rest of the configurations are given in Table S1–S15 of the supporting information.” The interaction energies and interaction distances are the important stability indices of the complexes (Figs. 1–3


                        ).

The order of charge transfer for the complexes of oxygen is in the following order i.e. O2@Ag6-coronene (−1.535

                              e

                        ) > O2@Ag6 (−1.470


                              e

                        ) > O2@coronene (−0.098


                              e

                        ) > O2@coronene-Ag6 (−0.095


                              e

                        ). In these complexes, the direction of charge transfer is from substrate towards oxygen molecule. The greater amount of charge transfer from substrate to p-orbital of oxygen is due to its high electronegativity.

The decreasing order of charge transfer is as follows; C2H5OH@Ag6-coronene (0.075


                              e

                        ) > C2H5OH@Ag6 (0.061


                              e

                        ) > C2H5OH@coronene (−0.009


                              e

                        ) > C2H5OH@coronene (0.007


                              e

                        ). The direction of charge transfer is from analyte towards substrate in all ethanol complexes except C2H5OH@coronene where the charge is transferred towards analyte.

In all of the complexes of both NH3 and H2S, the order of the amount of charge transfer is the same. The following order of the amount of charge transfer is observed; NH3@Ag6 (0.069


                              e

                        ) > NH3@Ag6-coronene (0.061


                              e

                        ) > NH3@coronene-Ag6 (0.006


                              e

                        ) > NH3@coronene (

                              −

                        0.003


                              e

                        ) and H2S@Ag6 (0.081


                              e

                        ) > H2S@Ag6-coronene (0.045


                              e

                        ) > H2S@coronene-Ag6 (0.081


                              e

                        ) > H2S@coronene (

                              −

                        0.001


                              e

                        ). The less amount of charge transfer in the complexes of NH3 and H2S compared to oxygen is due to the low electronegativity of nitrogen and sulfur atoms than an oxygen atom. Additionally, in these complexes, the direction of charge transfer is from the analyte towards the substrate.

The number of available energy states as a function of energy per unit volume in DOS spectra is a valuable indicator to understand the interaction mechanism (see Fig. 4
                        ). The degree of degeneracy is related to the intensity of energy states in DOS spectra. The DOS spectra for the complexes of analytes with silver-coronene configuration (analyte@Ag6-coronene) are given in Fig. 5
                        , whereas DOS spectra for the rest of the complexes are given in supporting information.

Excited state calculations play a vital role to understand the sensing mechanism of complexes (Table 2
                        ). The variation in absorption maximum (


                                 λ
                                 max


                        ), excitation energy and oscillator strength (

                              f
                              )

                         on interaction provide a useful way to explore the ability of a system to serve as a chemical sensor with visual changes upon interactions with the analyte. UV–Visible spectral visualization of the complexes is given in Fig. 6
                        .

Results of CDA for the adsorption of analytes over silver-coronene are presented in Table 3
                         (for the rest of the complexes see supporting information). CDA analysis reveals that, in most of the fragment pairs of the complexes, charge transfer through backdonation dominates over the donation. In NH3–Ag6 (0.244


                              e

                        ) and H2S-coronene (0.000


                              e

                        ) fragment pairs of NH3@Ag6 and H2S@conene complexes, the charge is transferred via donation rather than backdonation. Also, in O2–Ag6 (0.034


                              e

                        ) and Ag6-coronene (0.003


                              e

                        ) fragments pairs of O2@Ag6-coronene complex, charge transfer through donation is dominating over backdonation.

Silver cluster decorated graphene composites are promising sensor for the detection of NH3, H2S, O2, and C2H5OH molecules. The highest interaction energy is observed in O2@Ag6-coronene (−61.06 kcal mol−1
                     ) whereas the least Eint is seen in NH3@coronene (−4.00 kcal mol−1
                     ) complex. The oxygen molecules firmly bind with the silver-coronene surface due to strong Ag⋯O electrostatic interactions. High charge transfer is observed in O2@Ag6-coronene (−1.535


                           e

                     ) while least in H2S@coronene (0.001


                           e

                     ) and C2H5OH@coronene-Ag6 (0.001

                           e

                     ) complexes. NBO charge is transferred towards oxygen molecule due to its high electronegativity. The highest red shift of 


                              λ
                              max


                      (11%) and greater reduction in H-Lgap (42.5%) are observed in the O2@coronene-Ag6 complex. The appearance of a greater number of new energy states closer to the Fermi Level in occupied and virtual orbitals in DOS spectra, authenticate the higher sensitivity of silver-coronene towards oxygen. The density of HOMO is located over the silver cluster in the analyte@silver cluster and analyte@silver-coronene complexes. Charge transfer via backdonation is more prominent than a donation in most of the fragments pairs of the complexes. NCI results reveal the presence of electrostatic and dispersion interactions besides steric clashes in analyte@silver-coronene complexes. The better sensing properties of silver-coronene are due to the synergistic effect of both components in the composite. The outcome of the current study will provide a guideline to design silver-graphene sensors for the selective detection of gaseous analytes.
